        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down.</hi> | Beckenham | <hi rend="print">Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Mar 13 1871</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your valuable letter. I am strongly inclined to think that I have made a great &amp; complete oversight with respect to the subject which you discuss. I am the more surprised at this, as I remember reflecting on some points which ought to have led me to your conclusion.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>By an odd chance, I received the day before yesterday a letter from Mr Lowne (author of an excellent book on the anatomy of the Blow-fly) with a discussion very nearly to the same effect as yours.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> His conclusions were drawn from studying male insects with great horns, mandibles &amp;c. He informs me that his paper on this subject will soon be published in the Transact. Entomolog. Soc.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I am inclined to look at your &amp; Mr Lowne’s view as specially valuable from probably throwing light on the greater variability of male than female animals, which manifestly has much bearing on sexual selection. I will keep your remarks in mind whenever a new edition of my book is demanded.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>With my best thanks | I remain my dear Sir | In Haste | yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7564.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. B. Murdoch, 10 March 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3015.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Benjamin Thompson Lowne</ref> has not been found, but CD’s inscribed and annotated copy of Lowne 1870 is in the Darwin Library–CUL (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 510).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The reference is to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4903.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Lowne 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, pp. 224–5, CD added a section on the greater variability of male than of female animals, but did not cite Murdoch or Lowne.</note>
